How can I use MICA?

Great question! MICA will need to do some initial calculations when you first open it up (theres also been some strange behaviour in the Microsoft Edge browser, but it seems to work in both Chrome and Firefox). Hit Lets go to get started.

Confusion between minerals.

Upon opening of MICA and clicking past the splash scene, youll be brought to the mineral confusion tab, which will allow you to select a mineral and chose the closest n number of minerals in reduced dimensionality space. This might seem a little difficult to understand initially, but its easiest to understand if you apply this to a problem.

If you select Goethite from the drop down menu and 10, from the number of confusing minerals. Youll get a similar graph to the following (therell be some slight difference due to the fact that that the UWOT implimentation will produce a different result, but the interpretation of this plot will remain the same).

Goethite and its 10 most similar minerals in 2D reduced dimensionality space

The first thing youll notice is theres a green circle around one of the points - this marker is the location of the mineral that youve selected. You can use the functionality in the upper right hand corner of the plot to zoom into a particuar region of interest and look at minerals in more detail.

Minerals (and mineral formulas)

If you use either the lasso or box select tool to select a subset of mineral in the dataset, youll be brought to the minerals tab, which will give the chemical formula of each mineral inside your selected window.

Plot zoomed into copper-sulphide region, with a particular subset highlighted, showing their mineral formulas

Elements (and elemental formulas)

Selecting several minerals also lets you identify the important elements that makes them similar in the first place. MICA ranks the elemental importance of the mineral similarity measure. This rank is found by running an unsupervised Random Forest model through the selected minerals and extracting the elemental importance using the mean decrease in the Gini coefficient.

Key elements for selected copper-sulphide minerals
